Day - 9, 10 & 11 - Exploratory Data Analytics

Rajeev

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is an approach/philosophy for data analysis that employs a variety of techniques, mostly graphical, to display data in such a way that interesting features will become apparent. We use EDA to get insight into data set, uncover underlying structures in data, extract important variables, detect outliers and anomalies in data, test underlying assumptions about data, develop parsimonious models etc.

In these following modules, first I will demonstrate different kinds of simple graphs that can be useful in exploratory analyses and then I will explain how we can create those graphs using Rs plotting systems. In the end we will also do some case studies.

Exploratory Graphs

So far we have been using str(), summary() and table() functions to take a look at data and understand what it represents. But you can only understand little about the data using these functions. By creating plots we will be able to know a lot more about the data. In this section we will look into different kinds of simple graphs that can be used in exploratory analyses.

For this section we will be using the inbuilt data set in R, mtcars. The data was extracted from the 1974 Motor Trend US magazine, and comprises fuel consumption and 10 aspects of automobile design and performance for 32 automobiles (1973-74 models).

Lets have a look at the data set.

Here is a brief description of each variable in data set.

Each line of mtcars represents one model of car, which we can see in the row names. Each column is then one attribute of that car, such as the miles per gallon (or fuel efficiency), the number of cylinders, the displacement (or volume) of the cars engine in cubic inches, whether the car has an automatic or manual transmission, and so on.

Simple One Dimention plots

We will first look into simple one dimention summaries. When you first take a look at data set you would want to start with these simple summeries to get some insights on the data. There are 6 important kinds of one dimentional summaries.

  • Five-number Summary
  • Boxplots
  • Histograms
  • Density plots
  • Barplot
  • Dot plot

Five-number Summary

A five-number summary can be computed with the fivenum() function, it is actually the same as summary(). We get minimum, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile, maximum of the data variable and be able to quickly check how the data variable is distributed.

Here, we compute a five-number summary of the fuel efficiency variable mpg in mtcars data set. For interactive work, its often a bit nice to use the summary() function as it give nice headers unlike fivenum().

> fivenum(mtcars$mpg)
## [1] 10.40 15.35 19.20 22.80 33.90
> 
> # summary also give one more quantity, mean
> summary(mtcars$mpg)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   10.40   15.42   19.20   20.09   22.80   33.90

Boxplots

Boxplots are a visual representation of the five-number summary plus a bit more information. In particular, boxplots commonly plot outliers that go beyond the bulk of the data.

Here is an image describing barplot integrates five point summery into a graph.

Boxplot is implemented via the boxplot() function.

> # the col argument determines the color of box
> boxplot(mtcars$mpg, col = "cyan")

> 
> # box plot for "wt" variable
> boxplot(mtcars$wt, col = "cyan")

In our the boxplot for mpg variable there are on points outside the box, but in the box plot for wt variable there are a few points on the high end. These are called outliers, and it might be worth taking a look at them individually. Boxplots are especially good for examining outliers.

You can see from the boxplot that these points have wt greater than 5. We can get these variables using subset() function. Those are some heavy cars.

> subset(mtcars, mtcars$wt > 5)
##                      mpg cyl disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
## Cadillac Fleetwood  10.4   8  472 205 2.93 5.250 17.98  0  0    3    4
## Lincoln Continental 10.4   8  460 215 3.00 5.424 17.82  0  0    3    4
## Chrysler Imperial   14.7   8  440 230 3.23 5.345 17.42  0  0    3    4

Histograms

Histograms show the complete empirical distribution of the data, beyond the five data points shown by the boxplots. A histogram is useful to look at when we want to see more detail on the full distribution of the data. The boxplot is quick and handy, but fundamentally only gives us little information. Here, you can easily check skewwness of the data, symmetry, multi-modality, and other features.

We can use hist() function to generate a histogram.

> # histogram of "mpg" variable
> hist(mtcars$mpg, col = "cyan")

From this histogram you can see how fuel efficiency of various cars is distributed. A lot of cars have fuel efficiency in between 15 to 20 miles per gallon during 1973-74 period.

The hist() function by default determines the number of bars to use in the histogram based on the density of the data. However, you can override the default an argument breaks, we can use more bars to try to get more detail. In addition we can get a little more detail of we use the rug() function to show us the actual data points.

> hist(mtcars$mpg, col = "cyan", breaks = 25)
> 
> # shows the actual data points on x axis
> rug(mtcars$mpg)

Barplots

Barplots are useful for visualizing categorical data, with the number of entries for each category being proportional to the height of the bar.

In the mtcars dataset all variables are of numeric type. But actually some variables like am for example is basically a categorical variable, if am is 0 then it means the car has automatic transmission and if its 1 then manual.

The barplot can be made with the barplot() function. We use the table() function to do the actual tabulation of how many cars have automatc and manula transmission.

> table(mtcars$am)
## 
##  0  1 
## 19 13
> 
> barplot(table(mtcars$am), col = "cyan")

Looking at the barplot we can clearly see that more cars have automatic transmission.

Density plot

Density plots are usually a much more effective way to view the distribution of a variable. Create the plot using plot(density(x)) where x is a numeric vector.

> plot(density(mtcars$mpg))

Dot plot

A dot plot is a statistical chart consisting of all data points plotted on a fairly simple scale. You can create dot plots with the dotchart() function.

> dotchart(mtcars$mpg)

You can give lables to each point using labels argument and cex argument determines the character size of labels to be used.

> dotchart(mtcars$mpg, labels = row.names(mtcars), cex=.7)

Simple Two Dimention plots

So far we covered plotting tools for summarizing one dimentional data. Now we will see how we can investigate data in two dimentions. Some of the key approches are

  • Overlayed 1-D plots: using multiple boxplots and histograms to visualize one continuous and one categorical variable
  • Scatterplots: a natural plot for visualizing two continuous variables
  • Using color, size and shape to add dimentions: plotting points with different colors or shapes is useful for indicating a third dimension, where different colors can indicate different categories or ranges of something.
  • Smooth scatterplots:a variant of the usual scatterplot function which is useful in cases where there are too many points in the plot to be able to accurately represent each one. Its basically a 2-D histogram.

Multiple Boxplots

One of the simplest ways to show the relationship between two variables, when one variable is categorical and another one continusous is to show a side by side box plots.

Lets take mtcars$mpg and mtcars$am, one categorical and one continuous variable. By drawing a boxplot we can show the difference in mpg when the car is automatic transmitted(am = 0) or manual transmitted(am = 1).

The boxplot() function can take a formula, with the left hand side indicating the variable for which we want to create the boxplot (continuous) and the right hand side indicating the variable that stratifies the left hand side into categories. Since the region variable only has two categories, we end up with two boxplots, if it has n number categories we will get n box plots.

>  boxplot(mpg ~ am, data = mtcars, col = "cyan")

Side-by-side boxplots are useful because you can often fit many boxplots on a page to get a rich sense of any trends or changes in a variable accross different categories of another variable. Their compact format allow you to visualize a lot of data in a small space.

In the box plot we plotted we can see that fuel efficiency for manual transmitted cars is significantly higher.

Multiple Histograms

Similar to multiple box plots we can plot multiple histograms to see the changes in shapes of a variable across different categories. Here also we will have one categorical and one continusous variable. However, given histograms occupy more space compared to box plots, the number of histograms that you can effectively put on a page is limited.

There is no direct way to plot multiple histograms like for boxplots. Here is how we can create multiple histograms.

> par(mfrow = c(2,1), mar = c(4,4,2,1))
> 
> hist(subset(mtcars, am == 1)$mpg, col = "cyan", breaks = 15)
> hist(subset(mtcars, am == 0)$mpg, col = "cyan", breaks = 15)

The par() function is basically setting parameters for graphs. The goal of this section is to demonstrate graphs, so i will get get back to the specifics of such functions later. Here we used subset() function to subset mtcars when am = 1 and am = 0, and immediately indexing using the result with $ to get mpg column.

From the histograms we plotted we dont seem to get much relavant information. But that is all right, the main goal of exploratory data analysis is to look insights in data by plotting graphs. If we dont find any relationships between variables we move onto another variables.

Scatter plots

For continuous variables the most common visualization is scatter plots. We can visualize 2 continuous variables using scatter plots, which simply maps each variable to an x or y axis coordinate.

Here ia an example of scatter plot made using plot() function, on variables mpg and wt.

> plot(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$wt)

Using color in scatter plot

If we want to add a third dimension to the scatterplot above we could use color to highlight that dimension.

In the above scatter plot we can color the circles to indicate weather they are automatic transmitted(am = 0) or manula transmitted(am = 1).

> plot(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$wt, col = ifelse(mtcars$am == 1, "red", "black"))

Here col = ifelse(mtcars$am == 1, "red", "black") evaluates to black if am = 0 and red if am = 1. So black points are automatic and red ones are manual transmitted.

This is just an example showing how we can include color as a dimention, in later sections I will explain in detail how we can plot graphs such as this.

Multiple Scatter plots

Using multiple scatterplots can be necessary when overlaying points with different colors or shapes is confusing. Separating the plots out can sometimes make visualization easier. It is done similat to plotting multiple histograms, using the par() and plot() functions.

In these 2 plots we can see relation between mpg and wt when the cars are either automatic(am = 0) or manual transmitted(am = 1).

> par(mfrow = c(1, 2), mar = c(5, 4, 2, 1))
> 
> plot(subset(mtcars, am == 1)$mpg, subset(mtcars, am == 1)$wt)
> 
> plot(subset(mtcars, am == 0)$mpg, subset(mtcars, am == 0)$wt)

Smooth scatterplots

The smooth scatterplots are a variant of scatterplots which are useful in cases where there are too many points in the plot to be able to accurately represent each one. Smooth scatterplots are basically 2 dimentional histograms, these plots will visualize the distribution of data points similar to histograms.

We use smoothScatter() to make smooth scatterplots. Since we dont have too many points in mtcars dataset smooth scatterplots doesnt help all that much. But when we have lot of points usually smooth scatterplots are preffered.

> smoothScatter(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$wt)

Plotting Systems

Now that we are done with looking at different types of plots useful in exploratory data analysis, lets look at several ways how these plots can be plotted using R.

There are three different plotting systems in R and they each have different characteristics and modes of operation. They are

  • base plotting system
  • lattice system
  • ggplot2 system

In the following sections we will discuss each plotting system in detail.

Base Plotting System

The base plotting system is the original plotting system for R. All the functions we used in the last section such as boxplot(), plot(), hist() etc are from base plotting system. In the previous section we have seen how to draw using vaious types of plots using base plotting system in much more detail.

The base plotting system is often the most convenient plotting system to use because it mirrors how we sometimes think of building plots and analyzing data. If we dont have a completely well-formed idea of how we want to visualize some data, often well start by just making a simple plot and then slowly add more information to it as our thought process evolves.

The basic model is sometimes referred to as the artists palette model. The idea is you start with blank canvas and build up from there. There are two phases to creating a base plot: Drawing the plot, and then annotating it. We used functions like boxplot(), barplot(), hist(), dotchart(), plot(), smoothScatter(). Using these functions is usually the first step when using base plotting system for visualizing data. I wont go trough those functions again, you can refer the previsous section After this step we annotate the plot with several more useful details to the plots. We will look at several options to annotate in the following sections.

Plotting Parameters

All the base plotting functions we saw till now have a set of useful parameters which we can use to make our plots more detailed. Some of such important parameters include

  • pch: the plotting symbol (default is open circle)
  • xlab: character string for the x-axis label
  • ylab: character string for the y-axis label
  • main: main heading for plot
  • cex: size of points, specified as multiple of default point size
  • lty: the line type (default is solid line), can be dashed, dotted, etc.
  • lwd: the line width, specified as multiple of default line width
  • col: the plotting color, specified as a number, string, or hex code; or the colors() function
  • xlim: limits of x axis, given as vector c(min, max)
  • xlim: limits of y axis, given as vector c(min, max)
    function gives you a vector of colors by name
  • type: specifies the type of plot
> # pch demo
> x = rnorm(100)
> y = rnorm(100)
> 
> # gives circles by defalult without pch and size is double to the default one as we used cex = 2
> plot(x, y, cex = 2)

> 
> # givis solid points. there are several other options
> plot(x, y, pch = 20)

> 
> # xlab, ylab, main
> # xlab, ylab and main are assigned by default to the names of variables x, y and type of plot as main hedding. but if you want to customize use these parameters.
> plot(x, y, main = "Scatter Plot", xlab = "x axis", ylab = "y axis")

> 
> # col is used to change color
> plot(x,y, col = "green")

> hist(x, col = "green")

> 
> # lty and twd will change line type and width. useful when graphs have lines insterd of points, such as density plot.
> plot(density(x), lty = 4, lwd = 3)

> 
> # xlim and ylim basically sets limits for x and y axis
> # as you can see, the x and y axis are in between -1 and 1
> plot(x, y, xlim = c(-1,1), ylim = c(-1,1))

One final important parameter is type, it is only present in plot() function. As the name suggests, it detemines the type of the plot. If you use the plot() function without type argument it will give points, that is a scatter plot. Suppose if you use type = "l" you will get a curve.

> plot(1:10, rnorm(10), type = "l")

Overlaying Features

Once we start seeing interesting features in our data, its often useful to lay down annotations on our plots as reference points. For example consider a boxplot, we might want to draw a horizontal line at an important value.

Suppose we want to know cars which have mpg more than 20, we can draw a horizontal line at 20 to mark it. We do that using abline() function. The h parameter draws a horizontal line and v parameter draws

> boxplot(mtcars$mpg)
> abline(h = 20)

Similarly for histogram of mpg we would need to draw a vertical line. We do that using v parameter. You can also use col, lwd parameters for abline() function.

> hist(mtcars$mpg, breaks = 25, col = "cyan")
> abline(v = 20, col = "red", lwd = 3)

par function

The par() function is used to specify the global graphics parameters that affect all plots in an R session. If you specify a different value for a global parameter in your plot function then it will be overridden.

The par() function has several parameters such as:

  • las: the orientation of the axis annotations on the plot
  • col.lab: to change the color of axis lables
  • col.axis: to change color of axis annotations
  • col.main: to change color of main title
  • bg: the background color
  • mar: the margin size
  • oma: the outer margin size (default is 0 for all sides)
  • mfrow: number of plots per row, column (plots are filled row-wise)
  • mfcol: number of plots per row, column (plots are filled column-wise)

You can look at the documentation of par() function for more details on each parameter. Lets see the default parameter values for par() function. You can use par() command to view all default parameters. You get a list of all parameter default values. To see a default parameter of specific parameter, such as las try using par("las"). Note that this kind of behaviour doesnt appear for other function, for example if you type plot() you wont get list of default parameters, you get an error.

Observe the below plots and to see how default parameters are changed using par(). You can see that the background is changed to cyan, the axis lables to red, axis annotations to green and the main title to blue color.

> # histogram with default parameters
> hist(mtcars$mpg)

> 
> # setting parameters
> par(las = 2, col.lab = "red", col.axis = "green", col.main = "blue", bg = "cyan")
> 
> hist(mtcars$mpg)

Now to change the parameters back to default, try using dev.off(). 

> dev.off()
## null device 
##           1

The most importand parameters in par() are mar, mfrow, mfcol. They are useful in adjusting margins.

> par("mar")
## [1] 5.1 4.1 4.1 2.1
> par("mfcol")
## [1] 1 1
> par("mfrow")
## [1] 1 1

The mar parameter adjusts column widths in 4 corners of the plot and it takes 4 parameters. First parameter is for the bottomost corner and then the rest of them are followed in clockwise order.

You have seen use of mfrow when drawing multiple histograms or scatterplots earlier. It takes a vector of length 2 as argument. The first element states number of plots in a row and second states number of plots in a column. Only difference between mfrow and mfcol is that mfrow fills plots in row wise order and for mfcol they are filled column wise.

Lets look at the example we used to create multiple histograms. Here plots are created in 1 row and 2 columns in row wise order. Similarly margins are set for each

> par(mfrow = c(1, 2), mar = c(5, 4, 2, 1))
> 
> plot(subset(mtcars, am == 1)$mpg, subset(mtcars, am == 1)$wt)
> 
> plot(subset(mtcars, am == 0)$mpg, subset(mtcars, am == 0)$wt)

Some Annotation Functions

Here I will go through some key annotation functions.

  • lines(): add lines to a plot, given a vector of x values and a corresponding vector of y values (or a 2-column matrix); this function just connects the dots . points(): add points to a plot . text(): add text labels to a plot using specified x, y coordinates . title(): add annotations to x, y axis labels, title, subtitle, outer margin . mtext(): add arbitrary text to the margins (inner or outer) of the plot . axis(): adding axis ticks/labels

I will go through all these functions

Legends

Earlier we have seen that we can use colour as the third dimention in scatter plots. To know which points belongs to which category

> plot(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$wt, col = ifelse(mtcars$am == 1, "red", "black"))

Here in this plot if am is 1(manual) the point will be red in color and black otherwise. We can add a legend to the plot to mention this. To do that we use legend() function. The first argument specifies the position of legend, it can either be topleft or topright or bottomleft or bottomright. Then the legend parameter takes a vector of strings specifing the catogorical variable, such as automatic and malual. Then the col argument assignes color to respective values in legend parameter, like here automatic takes black color and manual takes red color. Finally, the pch argument specifies how the color markers are represented in legend. Using pch gives various shapes resembling points. You can also use lty parameter to specify them as lines.

> plot(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$wt, col = ifelse(mtcars$am == 1, "red", "black"))
> 
> legend("topleft", legend = c("automatic", "manual"), col = c("black", "red"), pch = 16)

Using lty in legend.

> plot(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$wt, col = ifelse(mtcars$am == 1, "red", "black"))
> 
> legend("topleft", legend = c("automatic", "manual"), col = c("black", "red"), lty = "solid")

One last thing about legends, for the first parameter we used topleft. Insterd of that we can give the coordinates to specify where we want the legend. But usually using topleft, topright, bottomleft, bottomright is prefarable.

> plot(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$wt, col = ifelse(mtcars$am == 1, "red", "black"))
> 
> legend(10, 3, legend = c("automatic", "manual"), col = c("black", "red"), lty = "dashed")

with function

While using plot function, suppose for scatter plots to write the commands such as plot(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$wt). This looks messy. To simply this we can use with() function. First argument is the data we want to use, and then you can give the plotting function without having to use $ to refer columns.

> with(mtcars, plot(mpg, wt))

You can also draw multiple plots in a single line with with() function. Hear is a plot using airquality data.

> par(mfrow = c(1, 3), mar = c(4, 4, 2, 1), oma = c(0, 0, 2, 0))
> with(airquality, 
+       { plot(Wind, Ozone, main = "Ozone and Wind")
+         plot(Solar.R, Ozone, main = "Ozone and Solar Radiation")
+         plot(Temp, Ozone, main = "Ozone and Temperature")
+         mtext("Ozone and Weather in New York City", outer = TRUE)
+       }
+     )

You can also use with() for any other functions also.

> with(mtcars, max(wt))
## [1] 5.424
> 
> with(mtcars, which.max(wt))
## [1] 16

Scatterplot matrix

Scatterplot matrix is a mtrix of scatterplots between all variables in dataset. It is useful to view relationships between variables. Its done using pairs() function. Usually this is the first step in analysing a dataset, as it displaces plots showing relationships between all variables. After looking at these plots we can dig deeper into the variables which show interesting patterns.

The diagonal is represented by variable name and each plot corresponds to the variables based on where that plot is located. The first plot on the top left beside mpg is a plot between mpg and cyl. The next one is between mpg and disp and so on.

> # scatterplot matrix for mtcars dataset
> pairs(mtcars)

Saving plots

Lattice Plotting System

The lattice plotting system is implemented in the lattice package which comes with every installation of R (although it is not loaded by default). To use the lattice plotting functions you must first load the lattice package with the library() function.

Lattice system is useful for plotting higher dimentional data, and for making many plots at once. Using base plotting system we saw how to plot multiple plots using mfrow argument. Lattice system optimizes that type of plots by providing many easy to use functions to make such plots.

The main difference between base and lattice plotting is that in lattice system we dont plot in phases like plotting first and then annotating with usful features. Here plotting and annotating is done with single function call.

> library(lattice)

ggplot2 System

ggplot2 is a plotting system for R, based on the grammar of graphics, which tries to take the good parts of base and lattice graphics and none of the bad parts. It takes care of many of the fiddly details that make plotting a hassle (like drawing legends) as well as providing a powerful model of graphics that makes it easy to produce complex multi-layered graphics.


The ggplot2 package, created by Hadley Wickham, offers a powerful graphics language for creating elegant and complex plots. Its popularity in the R community has exploded in recent years. Origianlly based on Leland Wilkinson's The Grammar of Graphics, ggplot2 allows you to create graphs that represent both univariate and multivariate numerical and categorical data in a straightforward manner. Grouping can be represented by color, symbol, size, and transparency. The creation of trellis plots (i.e., conditioning) is relatively simple.

To install a package, you can use the install.packages() function. 

install.packages("ggplot2")
To load a package into your current R session, use library(). 

library(ggplot2)

Scatterplots with qplot()

Lets look at how to create a scatterplot in ggplot2. Well use the iris data frame thats automatically loaded into R.
What does the data frame contain? We can use the head function to look at the first few rows.
head(iris) # by default, head displays the first 6 rows head(iris, n = 10) # we can also explicitly set the number of rows to display Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species 5.1 3.5 1.4 0.2 setosa 4.9 3.0 1.4 0.2 setosa 4.7 3.2 1.3 0.2 setosa 4.6 3.1 1.5 0.2 setosa 5.0 3.6 1.4 0.2 setosa 5.4 3.9 1.7 0.4 setosa

(The data frame actually contains three types of species: setosa, versicolor, and virginica.)

Lets plot Sepal.Length against Petal.Length using ggplot2s qplot() function.

qplot(Sepal.Length, Petal.Length, data = iris, color = Species) # dude!

To see where each species is located in this graph, we can color each point by adding a color = Species argument.

qplot(Sepal.Length, Petal.Length, data = iris, color = Species) # dude!

Similarly, we can let the size of each point denote sepal width, by adding a size = Sepal.Width argument.

qplot(Sepal.Length, Petal.Length, data = iris, color = Species, size = Petal.Width) # We see that Iris setosa flowers have the narrowest petals. qplot(Sepal.Length, Petal.Length, data = iris, color = Species, size = Petal.Width, alpha = I(0.7)) # By setting the alpha of each point to 0.7, we reduce the effects of overplotting. qplot(Sepal.Length, Petal.Length, data = iris, color = Species, xlab = "Sepal Length", ylab = "Petal Length", main = "Sepal vs. Petal Length in Fisher's Iris data")

This can give us a brief idea on how to use ggplot2.
